'''Tomáš Souček''' ({{IPA|cs|ˈtomaːʃ ˈsoutʃɛk}}; born 27 February 1995) is a Czech professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|WestHamU}} club [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] and the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic national team]].

==Club career==
===Slavia Prague===
Souček joined [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]]'s youth team at 10 years old,<ref name=bbcrep>{{Cite web|first=Lukáš|last=Vrablík|title=Tomas Soucek: West Ham midfielder's rise from rejection to Premier League star|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56001747|quote='He just wasn't good enough' – Soucek's rise|website=[[BBC Sport]]|date=11 February 2021}}</ref> after joining from hometown club [[FC Slovan Havlíčkův Brod|Slovan Havlíčkův Brod]]. Slovan Havlíčkův Brod subsequently netted £1.5&nbsp;million following Souček's transfer to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 2020, covering their running costs for the next ten years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tomas-soucek-transfer-news-west-ham-boyhood-club-ps1-5m-a4508291.html|title=Tomas Soucek's boyhood club 'bank £1.5m from West Ham transfer' which will cover budget for a decade|work=Evening Standard|date=25 July 2020|access-date=24 February 2022}}</ref> He had trials with two-second-tier clubs, [[MFK Frýdek-Místek|Frýdek-Místek]] and [[FC Sellier & Bellot Vlašim|Vlašim]], but they did not want to sign him.<ref name=bbcrep/> [[FK Viktoria Žižkov|Viktoria Žižkov]]’s manager, [[Jindřich Trpišovský]], watched Souček play and was not convinced of his ability but was persuaded to take him on a loan costing nothing to the club.<ref name=bbcrep/>

Souček made his league debut on 8 March 2015 in Viktoria Žižkov's 1–2 [[Czech National Football League]] home loss against [[FC Fastav Zlín]]. After returning to Slavia, he scored his first league goal on 16 August 2015 in Slavia Prague's 4–0 home win against [[FC Vysočina Jihlava]].<ref>{{cite web |date=16 August 2015 |title=Slavia – Jihlava 4:0, domácí si zastříleli a slaví první ligovou výhru |trans-title=Slavia – Jihlava 4:0, the home team scored freely and celebrates their first league win. |url=https://www.idnes.cz/fotbal/prvni-liga/slavia-jihlava-4-kolo-fotbalove-synot-ligy.A150816_153632_fotbal_pes |access-date=26 March 2024 |work=Mladá fronta DNES |language=cs}}</ref>

Souček broke into the Slavia Prague first team in 2015 and played 29 out of 30 league matches in the [[2015–16 Czech First League|2015–16]] [[Czech First League]] for them. However, in the [[2016–17 Czech First League|2016–17]] season, his position in the first team was lost due to the arrival of [[Michael Ngadeu-Ngadjui]] and Souček played only 93 minutes in three months between September and December 2016.<ref>{{cite web |date=2 December 2016 |title=RENTGEN: Štít Ngadeu? Řešení z nouze, které nyní táhne Slavii |trans-title=X-RAY: Ngadeu the Shield? A solution born out of necessity that is now driving Slavia. |url=http://isport.blesk.cz/clanek/fotbal-1-liga-rocnik-2016-17/287580/rentgen-stit-ngadeu-reseni-z-nouze-ktere-nyni-tahne-slavii.html |access-date=8 December 2016 |website=[[Blesk|iSport.cz]] |language=cs}}</ref> He went on loan to [[FC Slovan Liberec|Slovan Liberec]] during the winter transfer window, reuniting with former manager Trpišovský, who later managed Souček at Slavia Prague, following his appointment in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 June 2017 |title=Mám se vrátit do Slavie, víc neřeším, říká Souček před odletem na Euro |trans-title="I'm to return to Slavia, I'm not dealing with anything else," says Souček before flying to the Euros. |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/fotbalista-tomas-soucek-o-navratu-do-slavie-fes-/me-fotbal-2017.aspx?c=A170614_151547_me-fotbal-2017_pes |access-date=2 July 2017 |website=[[Mladá fronta Dnes]] |language=cs}}</ref>

On 9 May 2018, he played as Slavia Prague won the [[2017–18 Czech Cup]] final against [[FK Jablonec|Jablonec]].{{citation needed|date=January 2025}}

In the [[2018–19 SK Slavia Prague season|2018–19]] season, he won the domestic double with Slavia Prague and was awarded the Czech First League Player of the Year award.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 May 2019 |title=Nejlepším hráčem sezony je záložník Souček, koučem Trpišovský |trans-title=The best player of the season is midfielder Souček, the coach is Trpišovský. |url=https://www.idnes.cz/fotbal/prvni-liga/anketa-o-hrace-sezony-fotbalova-liga-soucek.A190527_202810_fotbal_ald |access-date=17 June 2019 |website=Mladá fronta Dnes |language=cs}}</ref> On 17 June 2019, Souček extended his contract with Slavia Prague until 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 June 2019 |title=Slavia roste, Tvrdík z toho někdy nespí. Cílem je LM i skončit bez ztráty |trans-title=Slavia is growing, and Tvrdík sometimes loses sleep over it. The goal is the Champions League and to finish without a defeat. |url=https://isport.blesk.cz/clanek/fotbal-1-liga-rocnik-2019-20/365004/slavia-roste-tvrdik-z-toho-nekdy-nespi-cilem-je-lm-i-skoncit-bez-ztraty.html |website=Blesk |language=cs}}</ref>

===West Ham United===
On 29 January 2020, Souček joined [[Premier League]] side West Ham United on an initial loan deal until the end of the [[2019–20 West Ham United F.C. season|2019–20 season]], with an option to make the transfer permanent in the summer.<ref name="WestHam">{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2020/january/29-january/west-ham-united-complete-loan-signing-czech-midfielder-tomas|title=West Ham United complete loan signing of Czech midfielder Tomáš Souček|website=West Ham United FC|date=29 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref> On 1 July, he scored his first goal for West Ham in a 3–2 win against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], having had a goal disallowed earlier in the same half by [[Video assistant referee|VAR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52080261|title=West Ham 3–2 Chelsea: Yarmolenko hits injury-time winner|work=BBC Sport |date=1 July 2020}}</ref> In West Ham's following league match, he scored again to give his team a 2–1 lead against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], in an eventual 2–2 away draw.<ref>{{Cite news|first1=Luke|last1=Edwards|first2=J. J.|last2=Bull|title=West Ham remain in relegation trouble after twice throwing away lead against Newcastle|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2020/07/05/newcastle-vs-west-ham-premier-league-live-score-latest-updates/|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=5 July 2020|access-date=6 July 2020|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> West Ham announced the permanent signing of Souček on 24 July 2020 on a four-year contract for a fee of around €21&nbsp;million (£19&nbsp;million).<ref>{{Cite web|date=24 July 2020|title=West Ham United complete €21m permanent Tomáš Souček transfer|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2020/july/24-july/west-ham-united-complete-eu21m-permanent-tomas-soucek-transfer|access-date=27 July 2020|website=West Ham United}}</ref> In August 2020, he was awarded the [[Golden Ball (Czech Republic)|Czech Golden Ball]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Záložník Souček poprvé vyhrál anketu Zlatý míč ČR o fotbalistu sezony |trans-title=Midfielder Souček won the Czech Republic Golden Ball poll for Footballer of the Season for the first time. |url=http://www.ksn.cz/aktuality/ankety/zaloznik-soucek-poprve-vyhral-anketu-zlaty-mic-cr-o-fotbalistu-sezony.html |access-date=5 August 2020 |website=ksn.cz |language=cs}}</ref>

On 1 January 2021, Souček scored the first [[Premier League]] goal of 2021 as West Ham beat [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] 1–0 at [[Goodison Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Soucek scores first goal of 2021, West Ham beats Everton|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/article/soucek-scores-first-goal-2021-west-ham-beats-everton/|website=SportsNet|date=1 January 2021}}</ref> During added time in a game against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 6 February, Souček was controversially sent off upon review after [[Video assistant referee|VAR]] appeared to show him strike [[Aleksandar Mitrović]] in the face; referee [[Mike Dean (referee)|Mike Dean]]'s decision was criticised by many of Souček's teammates, manager [[David Moyes]] and a number of pundits who protested Souček's innocence.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Michael|last=Emons|title=Fulham 0–0 West Ham United|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55867140|website=BBC Sport|date=6 February 2021|via=West Ham manager David Moyes called referee Mike Dean's decision to send off Tomas Soucek "embarrassing" as the Hammers drew with Fulham – and missed a chance to move into the top four of the Premier League.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Fulham 0–0 West Ham: Tomas Soucek sent off late on as Hammers miss top-four chance |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/12210496/fulham-0-0-west-ham-tomas-soucek-sent-off-late-on-as-hammers-miss-top-four-chance |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250528185053/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/12210496/fulham-0-0-west-ham-tomas-soucek-sent-off-late-on-as-hammers-miss-top-four-chance |archive-date=2025-05-28 |access-date=2025-06-15 |work=Sky Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref> West Ham launched an appeal to have the decision overturned in the aftermath.<ref>{{Cite web|title=West Ham United appeal Tomáš Souček red card|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/february/07-february/west-ham-united-appeal-tomas-soucek-red-card|website=West Ham United|date=7 February 2021}}</ref> On 8 February, the red card was rescinded.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Simon|last=Stone|title=Mike Dean: Referee notifies police over death threats to family|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55981926|website=BBC Sport|date=8 February 2021}}</ref> He finished the [[2020–21 Premier League|2020–21 season]] as West Ham's joint-top scorer, along with [[Michail Antonio]], both having scored ten goals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/clubs/25/West-Ham-United/stats|title=West Ham United FC Statistics|publisher=Premier League}}</ref> Souček's exploits during the 2020–21 season won him the [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]] award.<ref name=hoty>{{cite web|title=West Ham United supporters crown Tomáš Souček 2020/21 Betway Hammer of the Year!|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/august/06-august/west-ham-united-supporters-crown-tomas-soucek-202021-betway|publisher=West Ham United F.C.|date=6 August 2021|access-date=6 August 2021}}</ref>

On 7 June 2023, Souček played in the [[2023 UEFA Europa Conference League final]], against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] in Prague. West Ham won their first trophy in 43 years with a 2–1 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Steinberg |first=Jacob |date=2023-06-07 |title=Jarrod Bowen strikes at the last to earn Conference League glory for West Ham |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jun/07/fiorentina-west-ham-europa-conference-league-final-match-report |access-date=2025-06-15 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 1 January 2024, he signed a new contract with the club until 2027.<ref>{{cite web|title='I feel that this is my home now' – Soucek signs until 2027|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c06ypdr326zo|website=BBC Sport|date=1 January 2024}}</ref>

On 13 September 2025, Souček was sent-off in the 54th minute receiving a straight red card for a bad lunging foul on [[João Palhinha]] in their 3–0 home defeat to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. West Ham continued to struggle in 3 games ([[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]) in which he was suspended for.<ref>{{cite web | title=Tottenham cruise to victory over 10-man West Ham | website=BBC Sport | date=13 September 2025 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cdjzg9ev8wzt | access-date=7 November 2025}}</ref>

On 10 February 2026, Souček scored in West Ham’s 1–1 draw with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], his 39th Premier League goal, surpassing [[Patrik Berger]] as the highest scoring Czech in Premier League history.<ref>{{cite web |last=Agbobli|first= Joseph| title= Tomas Soucek breaks Premier League record help by Liverpool Legend  | website=daveockop | date=10 February 2026 | url=https://www.daveockop.com/latest-news/thomas-soucek-breaks-premier-league-record-held-by-liverpool-legend/ | access-date=7 November 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Tomáš Souček, Czech Rp.-Montenegro EURO 2020 QR 10-06-2019 (3).jpg|thumb|right|Souček with Czech Republic during the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] against Montenegro in 2019.]]
Souček appeared in all three matches of the [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic under-21 team]] in the [[2017 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2017 UEFA Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-09 |title=Tomáš Souček {{!}} Reprezentace |url=https://www.fotbal.cz/repre/hrac/hraci/4057 |access-date=2025-06-15 |website=Fotbal.cz |language=cs-CZ}}</ref> After representing the Czech Republic in several youth categories, Souček debuted for the [[Czech Republic national football team|senior team]] on 15 November 2016 in a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly match]] against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Češi neudrželi vedení a rozešli se s Dánskem remízou 1:1 |trans-title=The Czechs failed to hold onto their lead and drew 1–1 with Denmark. |url=https://www.eurofotbal.cz/pratelske-zapasy/mezinarodni/2016/reportaz/cesko-dansko-474045/ |access-date=2025-06-15 |website=EuroFotbal.cz |language=cs |quote=Do druhého poločasu poslal Karel Jarolím většinu zbývajících hráčů na lavičce náhradníků, svůj první start si tak připsali brankář Jiří Pavlenka a záložníci Petr Mareš s Tomášem Součkem. |trans-quote=As Karel Jarolím sent most of the remaining players on the bench in the second half, goalkeeper Jiří Pavlenka with midfielders Petr Mareš and Tomáš Souček debuted.}}</ref> He made his competitive debut on 10 June 2017, in Czech Republic's 1–1 away draw against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] in a [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2018 World Cup qualifier]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=iDNES.cz |date=2017-06-10 |title=Vpředu se Schickem, návrat Sivoka. Fanoušci proti Norsku věří i Součkovi |trans-title=Schick up front, Sivok's return. Fans also believe in Souček against Norway. |url=https://www.idnes.cz/fotbal/reprezentace/sestava-ctenaru-pred-fotbalovym-zapasem-norsko-cesko.A170609_101137_fot_reprez_pes |access-date=2025-06-15 |website=iDNES.cz}}</ref> On 24 March 2021, Souček scored a [[hat-trick]] in a 6–2 [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|World Cup qualifying]] win against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2021-03-24 |title=Estonia 2–6 Czech Republic: Tomas Soucek scores hat-trick in comfortable win |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56516156 |access-date=2025-06-15 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was a member of the Czech Republic squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020|Euro 2020]] where they were eliminated in the quarter-finals by [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Vladimír Coufal and Tomáš Souček called up by Czech Republic for UEFA Euro 2020 |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2021/may/24-may/vladimir-coufal-and-tomas-soucek-called-czech-republic-uefa-euro-2020 |access-date=2025-06-15 |website=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2021-07-02 |title=Czech Republic 1–2 Denmark: Impressive Danes reach semi-finals |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51198684 |access-date=2025-06-15 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Following the tournament, Souček was confirmed as the new captain of the Czech Republic, after [[Vladimír Darida]]'s retirement from international football.<ref>{{Cite news |agency=[[Czech News Agency]] |date=2021-07-14 |title=Souček si užívá dovolenou a těší se na roli kapitána: Možná bude víc rozhovorů |trans-title=Souček is enjoying his vacation and looking forward to the role of captain: "Maybe there will be more interviews." |url=https://www.denik.cz/fotbal/soucek-si-uziva-dovolenou-a-tesi-se-na-roli-kapitana-mozna-bude-vic-rozhovoru.html |access-date=2025-06-15 |work=[[Deník]] |language=cs|publisher=[[Vltava Labe Media]]}}</ref>

In May 2024, Souček was named as a member of the Czech Republic squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-05-28 |title=Euro 2024: West Ham's Tomas Soucek and Vladimir Coufal in Czech squad |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c0jj1k74nwgo |access-date=2025-06-15 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

In 2025, Souček was selected to the Czech Republic squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2026 World Cup qualification]] games. On 9 June against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], Souček scored his first goal of the tournament to bring Czechia level at 1–1. His team would go on to lose the match 5-1.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-09 |title=Croatia vs Czechia 5-1 |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/match-centre/match/520/288329/288330/400019386 |access-date=2026-01-24 |website=www.fifa.com}}</ref> Souček's second goal of the tournament was the fifth of six goals his team would score in a 6–0 victory against [[Gibraltar national football team|Gibraltar]] on 17 November.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-17 |title=Czechia vs Gibraltar 6-0 |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/match-centre/match/520/288329/288330/400019396 |access-date=2026-01-24 |website=FIFA}}</ref> Czech Republic ultimately finished second in [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group L|their group]], allowing them to advance to the second round of qualification. Following the match, Souček was stripped of captaincy of the national team, accused of ignoring Czech fans after the victory against Gibraltar.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 November 2025 |title=Czechia team punished for ignoring fans after 6-0 win |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/47012447/czechia-tomas-souceck-captain-squad-bonus-gibraltar |access-date=25 March 2026 |website=ESPN.com}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Souček has built a reputation as an energetic box-to-box midfielder with both defensive and attacking qualities.<ref name="WestHam" /> He is also known for his strong physical presence thanks to his {{height|m=1.92|precision=0}} frame.<ref name="WestHam" /> Souček was likened to [[Marouane Fellaini]] by [[José Mourinho]] due to his heading ability from set-pieces.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Jose Mourinho: West Ham lucky to draw; David Moyes has found his 'new Marouane Fellaini' in Tomas Soucek|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/12107921/jose-mourinho-west-ham-lucky-to-draw-david-moyes-has-found-his-new-marouane-fellaini-in-tomas-soucek|website=Sky Sports|date=19 October 2020}}</ref>

== Awards ==
On 18 March 2025 Souček was named Czech Footballer of the Year for the fourth time, equalling Pavel Nedvěd's record and trailing only [[Petr Čech]]'s nine awards. In 2024, Souček scored six goals for West Ham, and played 11 matches for the national team, scoring twice. He was instrumental in leading the Czechs to the elite division of the [[UEFA Nations League]]. Reflecting on his achievements, Souček expressed gratitude for being considered a role model and emphasised his ambition to continue scoring and inspiring young players.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lazarová|first=Daniela|date=18 March 2025 |title=Footballer of the Year Tomáš Souček: There are still many more goals to be scored |url=https://english.radio.cz/footballer-year-tomas-soucek-there-are-still-many-more-goals-be-scored-8845852 |access-date=2025-03-19 |website=[[Czech Radio]]|agency=[[Czech News Agency]]}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
In November 2025, Souček’s autobiography, titled ''Suk'', was published detailing his personal struggles with [[insomnia]] and [[Depression (mood)|depression]] during his career.<ref>{{cite web | last=Kilpatrick | first=Dan | title=West Ham’s Tomas Soucek considered retiring during ‘two years of horror’ with insomnia | website=The Athletic | date=11 November 2025 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6797382/2025/11/11/west-ham-news-tomas-soucek/ | access-date=12 November 2025}}</ref>

